0.body: Strata is a cutting-edge, robust and sleek Wayland compositor written in Rust using the Smithay library. It is designed to be minimal and flexible yet customizable. It is configured in Lua which makes it possible to add custom functions and scripts. The ability to extend the compositor using plugins will be added in the near future.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: Strata is a Wayland Compositor , which is very different from an X11 Window Manager. Strata includes both a server and a client, whereas in an X11 window manager, the WM only comes with the client. The rest is done by the Xorg server.
1.title: Some useful information

10.body: Strata is configured in Lua , a lightweight, high-level, multi-paradigm programming language. Lua allows you to customize Strata to a level which is very difficult to do in other config formats such as TOML or YAML.

4.body: Currently, to use Strata, you have to compile it from source using Rust.
4.title: Getting Started

5.breadcrumbs: Strata » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » Compiling from Source
5.title: Compiling from Source

6.body: To compile and use Strata, you need some dependencies which have to be installed using a package manager, such as pacman or apt, depending on your distro. The required dependencies are listed below: udev wayland wayland-protocols libinput libxkbcommon libglvnd seatd dbus-glib mesa If you're on Arch or any Arch based distro (such as Artix, Garuda, Manjaro, etc), you can install these using the following command: sudo pacman -S udev wayland wayland-protocols libinput libxkbcommon libglvnd seatd dbus-glib mesa If you're on Debian, or Debian based distros such as Ubuntu, Mate, Zorin, etc... you can install these using this command: sudo apt-get install libudev-dev libgbm-dev libxkbcommon-dev libegl1-mesa-dev libwayland-dev libinput-dev libdbus-1-dev libsystemd-dev libseat-dev
6.breadcrumbs: Strata » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » Dependencies
6.title: Dependencies

7.breadcrumbs: Strata » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » 1. Clone the repository
7.title: 1. Clone the repository

8.body: To install, cd into the cloned repo and then run: cargo install --path . This'll install it for your user. If you want to install it globally (which is not recommended right now), then run: sudo cargo install --path . You can sit back and relax while it installs Strata. It might take a bit of time since it has to compile the source code and all the dependencies but if your system is a bit better than a potato, this won't take much time.
8.breadcrumbs: Strata » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » 2. Compile and Install
8.title: 2. Compile and Install

9.body: Congratulations! If all went well, you should have Strata installed on your system. The next chapter will teach you how to configure Strata.
